WEBVTT

00:00:00.160 --> 00:00:05.840
Let's use multiple cursors with Posit's RStudio IDE. These can be super useful when you have to do

00:00:05.840 --> 00:00:10.000
finicky text manipulation tasks within a document or in your code. Let's see how all this works

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:13.280
running through your options with an example. Suppose we have this artist table and we want

00:00:13.280 --> 00:00:18.879
to convert it to a vector of just the artists. First, let's create a few extra cursors. We're

00:00:18.879 --> 00:00:23.760
going to use Option, Control, and then use the Up or Down arrow on a Mac, or Control and Alt

00:00:23.760 --> 00:00:27.760
and the Up or Down arrow on Windows. Now let's move around and select some text using the Shift

00:00:27.760 --> 00:00:31.440
and arrow keys. We're going to use Command and the arrow key to jump to the end of the line.

00:00:31.440 --> 00:00:36.080
Then use Shift and the Option key plus some arrows to select the comma and years. Note that we're

00:00:36.080 --> 00:00:40.880
selecting across multiple lines. And then backspace to delete that. And then on the keyboard, just

00:00:40.880 --> 00:00:45.200
Forward Delete to move all of these into one line. And now just a little bit of our code to convert

00:00:45.200 --> 00:00:50.400
these into a vector called artists. So far in this example, we use just keyboard shortcuts to create

00:00:50.400 --> 00:00:56.080
multiple cursors across multiple lines, but you could also use your mouse. On Windows, use Alt

00:00:56.080 --> 00:00:59.919
and then click and drag to select multiple lines. And then on a Mac, hold

